refined_goal: Build a zero-LLM endpoint defense and attribution system that lives on your PC, intercepts phishing across email, web, and files, and produces a cryptographically verifiable evidence graph that links attempts to their hosting infrastructure (domains, IPs, ASNs, certs, favicons, software stacks). Architecture: a Go/C# agent with deterministic pipelines (BK-tree domain lookalike detection, Unicode-confusables mapping, YARA/Sigma rules, JA3/TLS and favicon perceptual hashes, WHOIS/RDAP/CT scans), Docker-based detonation lab for attachments, and a React/ImGui UI. Success: <50 ms URL decision latency; 90%+ precision on brand lookalikes; automated evidence packs (PCAP, TLS, WHOIS) in <90 s; 0 user-mode crashes in 10k events; >95% safe redirect resolution coverage. Why it matters: it turns phishing from a vague social risk into a measurable, auditable infrastructure event you can block, explain, and lawfully report within minutes‚Äîwithout relying on any LLMs.
repository_synergy:
The insight: media downloaders are world-class at surviving hostile URLs. yt-dlp/youtube-dl carry years of hardened logic for decoding obfuscated redirects, JS signatures, and peculiar headers. Repurposed, they become a robust, sandbox-friendly URL normalizer and metadata miner for phishing links‚Äîno rendering, no JS execution, just deterministic peeling of redirect chains. Pair that with Moby‚Äôs containers to detonate attachments in tight boxes; PowerToys to surface protections natively in Windows workflows; and a React/ImGui split UI for both rich dashboards and instant, low-latency overlays.

Why these repos: yt-dlp/youtube-dl give us a Swiss army knife of URL handling that phishers inadvertently target (shorteners, embedded redirects, base64 blobs). LangChain‚Äîoddly, without an LLM‚Äîgives an elegant DAG to orchestrate tools, tracing, and retries with backoff; its Expression Language becomes a rule engine for deterministic functions. Ollama‚Äîalso without models‚Äîbecomes a clever offline artifact registry for signed rulepacks (YARA, Sigma, confusables maps, brand favicon hashes) using its simple pull/version workflow and local HTTP. PowerToys is the best-kept secret for Windows-native UX hooks (Run plugin, context menus, quick overlays). Moby supplies reproducible, ephemeral sandboxes to throw untrusted files into. React is our detailed analyst console; ImGui is our zero-latency alert overlay. trekhleb/javascript-algorithms provides the fundamentals (BK-tree, Levenshtein, Bloom filters) to make the heuristics fast and tight. PayloadsAllTheThings, curated responsibly, is a goldmine of real signatures to harden our detectors and build realistic detonation playbooks. Tabby provides a comfortable incident terminal. awesome-go points us to miekg/dns, gopacket, and geoip2‚Äîbattle-tested building blocks.

The synergy: treat yt-dlp‚Äôs extractor framework as the ‚Äúphish expander,‚Äù Moby as the ‚Äúglass box,‚Äù PowerToys as the ‚Äúnative glove,‚Äù and LangChain-as-DAG as the ‚Äúspinal cord.‚Äù Then abuse Ollama as a signed, offline content distribution network for rules and evidence schemas, not models. The innovation: you get a personal SIEM+sandbox that‚Äîinstead of guessing with an LLM‚Äîcollects verifiable indicators, attributes infrastructure through CT logs, WHOIS/RDAP, JA3 and icon hashes, and outputs a machine-checkable case bundle. The bridge: reframe two LLM-centric repos (LangChain, Ollama) into non-LLM infrastructure primitives; reframe media scrapers (yt-dlp/youtube-dl) into redirect peelers; reframe PowerToys into a stealthy endpoint HMI.
technical_architecture:
Components:
- Endpoint Agent (Go + C#):
  - URL Guard: browser and clipboard hooks capture outbound URLs; uses yt-dlp/youtube-dl extractors in --dump-json mode inside a netns-limited container to expand redirects and collect headers, TLS cert chain, and mime hints. No JS execution.
  - Domain Intelligence: trekhleb BK-tree and Levenshtein against a brand corpus; Unicode confusables map; TLD swaps; IDN punycode checks; Bloom filter of known-bad hashes. JA3/JA4 fingerprints for outbound TLS; FavHash (Murmur/xxHash of favicon bytes) for page fingerprinting when fetched via HEAD-range.
  - File Guard: File Explorer context menu (PowerToys plugin). On open or download, route to Detonation Lab.
  - Evidence Graph: local immutable log (Merkle-tree with Blake3) stores indicators (URL‚ÜíIP‚ÜíASN‚ÜíCERT CN‚ÜíCT entry‚ÜíFavicon hash). Graph serialized to signed JSON-LD.
- Detonation Lab (Moby):
  - Disposable containers (gVisor/AppArmor): Office/PDF detonation via libreoffice-headless (for macro extraction), oletools/pdfid/pdf-parser, capa for PE triage, YARA scan. Network egress blocked, but PCAP loopback capture with gopacket for full trace of any attempt.
  - Suricata plug-in for rules-based behavior; Sigma rules for Windows event mirroring (where applicable via ETW mirrors in user-mode).
- Rulepack Registry (Ollama repurposed): signed tarballs of rules (YARA/Sigma), brand corpora, confusables, Favicon hashes, and playbooks; versioned by tag, pulled offline (no LLM). Local HTTP serves rule manifests to Agent.
- Orchestrator (LangChain LCEL without models): DAG of pure functions with retries; callbacks provide structured tracing. E.g., Email Intake ‚Üí URL Extract ‚Üí Expand ‚Üí Heuristics ‚Üí Evidence ‚Üí Verdict ‚Üí UI.
- UI:
  - React Analyst Console: case timeline, graph visualization, one-click report generator (abuse@, CERT). Training microdrills (freeCodeCamp style) simulate safe phish to improve user reflexes.
  - ImGui Overlay: 20‚Äì40 ms heads-up when a lookalike or suspicious chain is clicked; offers Open in Sandboxed Browser or Block.
  - Tabby Terminal: incident console embedding CLI tools (WHOIS, RDAP, dig) proxied through the Agent for logged queries.

APIs and protocols:
- Agent‚ÜîLab: gRPC over Unix/Named Pipes; protobuf for evidence and task spec.
- Agent‚ÜîUI: localhost HTTP/WS; Server-Sent Events for live alerts.
- Registry: localhost Ollama-like REST endpoints mapping to rulepack pulls; SHA256/Ed25519 signatures.

Performance and defenses:
- Cache expanded redirects and DNS answers with TTL; Bloom filters prefilter brands; BK-tree preheated in memory-mapped file for O(log n) lookups.
- Sandbox creates network namespaces with BPF egress filter; timeboxed runs (e.g., 30s) and CPU caps avoid hangs.
- All untrusted parsing occurs in containers; the Agent only ingests structured outputs.
- Evidence Pack Builder uses deterministic hashes (Blake3) for reproducibility.

Integration patterns:
- PowerToys plugin calls Agent via local HTTP for file/URL analysis.
- yt-dlp custom extractor: ‚ÄúCredentialHarvesterGeneric‚Äù searches DOM statically (no JS) for common phish forms, CSRF-less posts, and brand assets; returns structured signals.
- awesome-go libs: miekg/dns for RDNS/NS walking; oschwald/geoip2 for ASN; gopacket for PCAP; cert parsing via crypto/x509; JA3 calculation.
- PayloadsAllTheThings informs detonation playbooks and YARA samples, curated and sandbox-confined.
expected_impact:
- One-click Quarantine with Context: User downloads an invoice.docm. PowerToys context menu triggers detonation; oletools reveals macros contacting a known C2 ASN. Evidence pack with YARA hits, CT logs of cert reuse, and PCAP is generated and the file is sealed.
- Redirect Peeler for SMS Phish: Clipboard catch of bit.ly link. yt-dlp expands to a cloaked domain with IDN lookalike of a bank; FavHash matches known phish kit favicon. Overlay blocks with provenance shown and safe contact options.
- Corporate Brand Protections at the Edge: BK-tree detects lookalikes of your own domain in inbound links. Auto-submits abuse-ready takedown evidence (WHOIS, RDAP, hosting contact) with signed bundle.
- USB Drop Defense: New EXE from USB triggers sandbox run; capa classifies as RAT family; egress attempts recorded, blocked, and correlated to a domain from a recent email‚Äîtying a campaign together.
- Macro-less PDF Trap: pdfid flags suspicious JS; Suricata rules fire on extracted URLs; the Agent crosslinks to CT log entries showing the cert minted 2 hours ago.
- Training Microdrills: FreeCodeCamp-style React modules periodically simulate safe phish in the user‚Äôs environment, measuring reflexes and improving overlay UX based on behavior.
- Team-Ready Evidence: Graph JSON-LD exports to your IR platform; Manim renders a short animation timeline for leadership.

Limitations and mitigations:
- Human attribution is out of scope; we attribute infrastructure only and provide reporting workflows (no vigilante action).
- Some phish use JS/Canvas gating; we avoid JS execution for safety‚Äîusers can open a sealed sandboxed browser to inspect.
- Sandbox evasion exists; multiple base images and behavior rules mitigate but not eliminate evasion.
- OS integrations vary; on macOS/Linux we use equivalent hooks instead of PowerToys.
innovation_analysis:
Innovation score: 8.6/10. The twist‚Äîabusing media downloaders for safe redirect peeling, using LLM-era infra (LangChain, Ollama) as a deterministic pipeline and rule registry, and fusing Moby sandboxes with Windows-native PowerToys UX‚Äîyields a personal, verifiable, zero-LLM threat lab on every PC.

Next steps (2 weeks):
- Build the URL Guard prototype: BK-tree domain lookalike + yt-dlp expander in a netns container; ImGui overlay MVP.
- Detonation Lab: Dockerfile with oletools/pdfid/capa/YARA; gRPC schema for tasks/evidence.
- Rulepack registry: sign and serve initial corpora via repurposed Ollama pull.
- PowerToys plugin: context menu + Run command wired to Agent.

Key metrics:
- URL decision latency; redirect coverage; lookalike precision/recall; sandbox detonation throughput; evidence pack reproducibility rate.

Essential tools:
- Go, C#, React, ImGui, Moby, yt-dlp/youtube-dl, YARA/Sigma, Suricata, gopacket, miekg/dns, Blake3, Ed25519.

![Moby Project logo](docs/static_files/moby-project-logo.png "The Moby Project")

Moby is an open-source project created by Docker to enable and accelerate software containerization.

It provides a "Lego set" of toolkit components, the framework for assembling them into custom container-based systems, and a place for all container enthusiasts and professionals to experiment and exchange ideas.
Components include container build tools, a container registry, orchestration tools, a runtime and more, and these can be used as building blocks in conjunction with other tools and projects.

## Principles

Moby is an open project guided by strong principles, aiming to be modular, flexible and without too strong an opinion on user experience.
It is open to the community to help set its direction.

- Modular: the project includes lots of components that have well-defined functions and APIs that work together.
- Batteries included but swappable: Moby includes enough components to build fully featured container systems, but its modular architecture ensures that most of the components can be swapped by different implementations.
- Usable security: Moby provides secure defaults without compromising usability.
- Developer focused: The APIs are intended to be functional and useful to build powerful tools.
They are not necessarily intended as end user tools but as components aimed a

React is a JavaScript library for building user interfaces.

* **Declarative:** React makes it painless to create interactive UIs. Design simple views for each state in your application, and React will efficiently update and render just the right components when your data changes. Declarative views make your code more predictable, simpler to understand, and easier to debug.
* **Component-Based:** Build encapsulated components that manage their own state, then compose them to make complex UIs. Since component logic is written in JavaScript instead of templates, you can easily pass rich data through your app and keep the state out of the DOM.
* **Learn Once, Write Anywhere:** We don't make assumptions about the rest of your technology stack, so you can develop new features in React without rewriting existing code. React can also render on the server using [Node](https://nodejs.org/en) and power mobile apps using [React Native](https://reactnative.dev/).

[Learn how to use React in your project](https://react.dev/learn).

# screenshot-to-code

A simple tool to convert screenshots, mockups and Figma designs into clean, functional code using AI. Now supporting Claude Sonnet 3.7!

https://github.com/abi/screenshot-to-code/assets/23818/6cebadae-2fe3-4986-ac6a-8fb9db030045

Supported stacks:

- HTML + Tailwind
- HTML + CSS
- React + Tailwind
- Vue + Tailwind
- Bootstrap
- Ionic + Tailwind
- SVG

Supported AI models:

- Claude Sonnet 3.7 - Best model!
- GPT-4o - also recommended!
- DALL-E 3 or Flux Schnell (using Replicate) for image generation

See the [Examples](#-examples) section below for more demos.

We also just added experimental support for taking a video/screen recording of a website in action and turning that into a functional prototype.

![google in app quick 3](https://github.com/abi/screenshot-to-code/assets/23818/8758ffa4-9483-4b9b-bb66-abd6d1594c33)

[Learn more about video here](https://github.com/abi/screenshot-to-code/wiki/Screen-Recording-to-Code).

[Follow me on Twitter for updates](https://twitter.com/_abi_).

## üåç Hosted Version

[Try it live on the hosted version (paid)](https://screenshottocode.com).

## üõ† Getting Started

The app has a React/Vite frontend and a FastAPI backend.

Keys needed:

- [OpenAI API key with access to GPT-4](https://github.com/abi/screenshot-to-code/blob/main/Troubleshooting.md) or Anthropic key (optional)
- Both are recommended so you can compare results from both Claude and GPT4o

If you'd like to run the app with Ollama open source models (not recommended due to poor quality results), [follow this comment](https://github.com/abi/screenshot-to-code/issues/354#issuecomment-2435479853).

Run the backend (I use Poetry for package management - `pip install --upgrade poetry` if you don't have it):

```bash
cd backend
echo "OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-your-key" > .env
echo "ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=your-key" > .env
poetry install
poetry shell
poetry run uvicorn main:app --reload --port 7001
```

# INSTALLATION

To install it right away for all UNIX users (Linux, macOS, etc.), type:

    sudo curl -L https://yt-dl.org/downloads/latest/youtube-dl -o /usr/local/bin/youtube-dl
    sudo chmod a+rx /usr/local/bin/youtube-dl

If you do not have curl, you can alternatively use a recent wget:

    sudo wget https://yt-dl.org/downloads/latest/youtube-dl -O /usr/local/bin/youtube-dl
    sudo chmod a+rx /usr/local/bin/youtube-dl

Windows users can [download an .exe file](https://yt-dl.org/latest/youtube-dl.exe) and place it in any location on their [PATH](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PATH_%28variable%29) except for `%SYSTEMROOT%\System32` (e.g. **do not** put in `C:\Windows\System32`).

You can also use pip:

    sudo -H pip install --upgrade youtube-dl

This command will update youtube-dl if you have already installed it. See the [pypi page](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/youtube_dl) for more information.

macOS users can install youtube-dl with [Homebrew](https://brew.sh/):

    brew install youtube-dl

Or with [MacPorts](https://www.macports.org/):

    sudo port install youtube-dl

Alternatively, refer to the [developer instructions](#developer-instructions) for how to check out and work with the git repository. For further options, including PGP signatures, see the [youtube-dl Download Page](https://ytdl-org.github.io/youtube-dl/download.html).
